result.execSummary:
The defendant Kyle E Hensley was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Burglary-Building or Dwelling [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class F felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.10(1m)(a).
  • Criminal Damage to Property (Over $2500) [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.01(2)(d).
  • Bail Jumping-Misdemeanor, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(a).
  • Obstructing an Officer, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 946.41(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Email from Jennifer Eaton of NWTC to DOC Agent Jackie Scholten indicating where defendant is at with the GED/HSED program.

Defendant Kyle E Hensley in court.  Raymond Pelrine appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Probation Agent Jackie Scholten present in court. Court reviews events in file, questions defendant on how he's doing on probation. Defendant is working full-time at Wiretech. He's started his community service, he's completed his HSED and has to complete 3 tests get his GED. Agent Scholten indicates defendant has made 2 payments and has completed 13 hours of community service so far. Once he gets a few more paychecks under his belt, DOC will set up a wage assignment. Agent Scholten indicates defendant is doing everything she's asked of him. Court commends defendant on improvements made since last hearing. Court won't set another probation review hearing, Agent Scholten can request one if she feels it's needed.

Defendant Kyle E Hensley in court.  Joan M. Korb appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Probation Agent Jackie Scholten present in court. Victim, Mary Gilbert of the Historical Society also present in court. Court reviews events in file, reviews sentence previously imposed. Court questions defendant on how probation is going. Defendant is not working, hasn't paid anything toward financial obligations. Defendant waiting to hear from NEW Industries to see if he had a job there. Defendant hasn't completed community service nor has he gotten his GED/HSED. Court lifts stay on 60 days jail time. Huber release is granted.  Probation review hearing scheduled for September 24, 2015 at 03:00 pm.

Defendant Kyle E Hensley in court.  Joan M. Korb appeared for the State of Wisconsin. Probation Agent Jackie Scholten present in court. Court reviews events in file, reviews sentence previously imposed. Court questions defendant on employment and how probation is going. Defendant has completed the apology letter and compas evaluation, no further counseling needed. Defendant not working, hasn't done the community service, doesn't have a high school diploma, isn't paying toward financial obligations. Court strongly encourages defendant to start complying with conditions of probation, sets another probation review hearing. If defendant hasn't made any progress, court may lift the stay on the jail time. If defendant is working and complying with conditions of probation, including paying toward financial obligations, Agent Scholten can request the hearing be removed from the calendar.  Probation review hearing scheduled for May 22, 2015 at 03:00 pm.

records.addlTxt: Defendant Kyle E Hensley in court with attorney Gregory A Gerbers.  Defendant Kyle E Hensley in custody.  Joan M Korb appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Minute sheet. State gives plea agreement.  Court questions defendant on change of plea.  Rights/elements/max. penalties reviewed with defendant.  Defendant enters no contest plea to Cts. 1, 2. 7 & 10. Defense stipulates to factual basis to accept plea.  Court finds pleas made freely, knowingly and voluntarily, accepts pleas, and finds guilty of Cts. 1, 2, 7 & 10. Court dismisses remaining counts but reads in for sentencing purposes. Court reviews collateral consequences, possible penalties for felony conviction with defendant. Defendant must submit a DNA sample to the State of Wisconsin within 10 days and pay the $250 DNA surcharge. State/Defense ready to proceed to sentencing without the benefit of a PSI.  Victim makes statement to court.  Bond is no longer in effect.
